<section xml:id="sec-multilevel-data">
  <title>Multilevel Data</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Many real-world problems require data collected at multiple levels; for example, individuals within households, classrooms within schools, or schools within districts. This topic introduces the concept of multilevel data structures, explaining how they are organised, why they matter, and how they can be analysed effectively.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>By the end of this topic you will be able to:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Identify examples of datasets with multiple levels.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Describe the characteristics and structure of multilevel data.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Apply basic methods to explore and prepare multilevel data for analysis.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Analyse multilevel datasets using appropriate statistical techniques.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-multilevel-tasks">
    <title>Your Tasks</title>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>Read and watch the materials on the concept of Multilevel Data, and respond to the discussion board.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Engage in a forum discussion on challenges with multivariate data.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Attempt the assignment on giving 300 words on either the MICS data or another data set.</p>
        </li>
